        <h2>1. Procore — Best all-in-one platform for commercial GCs</h2>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> Custom (contact sales)</p>

        <p>Procore doesn't have a native CPM scheduling engine — it integrates with Primavera P6 and Microsoft Project instead. What it does is serve as the hub where your schedule, your documents, your RFIs, your submittals, and your financials all live together. The schedule integration means field teams can access the current schedule on their phones without the estimating department handing out PDF printouts.</p>

        <p>For commercial GCs who already use Procore as their PM backbone, the scheduling integration is the practical choice. The alternative — maintaining a separate schedule in P6 and manually keeping Procore in sync — is a recipe for drift and miscommunication.</p>

        <h2>2. Primavera P6 — Industry gold standard for large/complex projects</h2>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> ~$300+/user/month (Oracle Cloud)</p>

        <p>If your projects are large ($50M+), complex (multi-phase, multi-prime), or public (government contracts requiring schedule submittals), Primavera P6 is often required, not optional. Owners on major public works projects frequently mandate P6-formatted schedule deliverables. P6's CPM engine handles true critical path analysis, resource leveling, and baseline comparisons at a depth that no other tool matches.</p>

        <p>The trade-off: P6 is expensive, requires specialist training to use properly, and is overkill for projects under $10–15M. Most commercial GCs have one or two people who can run P6; it's not a tool your superintendent uses in the field.</p>

        <h2>3. Microsoft Project — Accessible CPM for mid-size commercial work</h2>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $10–$55/user/mo (Project Plan 1–5)</p>

        <p>Microsoft Project is the middle ground between spreadsheet Gantt charts and full P6. It handles CPM scheduling with task dependencies, critical path highlighting, and resource tracking. It integrates natively with the Microsoft 365 ecosystem that most commercial contractors already use. For GCs running projects in the $2–$30M range, MS Project is often the most practical choice — familiar, functional, and affordable.</p>

        <p>The weakness: it's not built for construction specifically. You don't get construction-specific templates, sub assignment workflows, or field-facing mobile views out of the box.</p>

        <h2>4. Autodesk Build — Best for mid-large commercial projects in the Autodesk ecosystem</h2>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> Custom</p>

        <p>Autodesk Build (formerly BIM 360 + PlanGrid combined) includes a scheduling module with Gantt views, lookahead scheduling (2-week and 4-week pull plans), and milestone tracking. It integrates natively with Autodesk's broader construction cloud — drawings, RFIs, submittals, and field issues all connect. For GCs already using Autodesk for BIM and drawing management, Build's scheduling tools reduce the total number of platforms in play.</p>

        <h2>5. Fieldwire — Best for field-level short-interval scheduling</h2>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> Free–$54/user/mo</p>

        <p>Fieldwire isn't a CPM scheduling tool — don't expect critical path analysis. What it is, is excellent for field crews: task-based scheduling tied to specific plan locations, punch lists, daily reports, and real-time status updates. Many commercial GCs use Fieldwire alongside P6 or MS Project — the master schedule lives in P6, while daily/weekly field coordination happens in Fieldwire where subs can actually access it on their phones.</p>

        <h2>What to look for in commercial scheduling software</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Critical path method (CPM)</strong> — Can the tool identify your true critical path and model the impact of delays?</li>
          <li><strong>Baseline comparison</strong> — Can you compare current schedule to original contract baseline?</li>
          <li><strong>Sub-level visibility</strong> — Can subs access their work windows without seeing your full master schedule?</li>
          <li><strong>Integration with your PM platform</strong> — Does it connect to Procore, Autodesk, or your ERP?</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile access</strong> — Can field superintendents view the schedule on-site without carrying a laptop?</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule deliverable format</strong> — Can it export in the format your owner or GC requires?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Do I need Primavera P6 for commercial construction?</h3>
        <p>For projects under $15–20M, probably not. P6 is the right tool when your owner requires CPM schedule submittals in P6 format, your projects are large and complex enough that simplified Gantt tools break down, or you're doing public works where schedule documentation is contractually mandated. For most commercial GCs under that threshold, Microsoft Project or the scheduling module in your PM platform is sufficient.</p>

        <h3>Can Procore do CPM scheduling?</h3>
        <p>Not natively. Procore integrates with Primavera P6 and Microsoft Project, pulling schedule data into its interface for distribution and tracking. It doesn't build or calculate CPM schedules internally. Think of it as the distribution and collaboration layer, with P6 or MS Project as the scheduling engine.</p>

        <h3>What about 4D BIM scheduling?</h3>
        <p>4D BIM links your 3D model to your schedule so you can visualize construction sequencing. Tools like Autodesk Navisworks and Synchro handle this. It's primarily used on large, complex projects where clash detection and sequencing visualization provide real value. Most commercial GCs don't use it on projects under $30–40M.</p>

